:::summary
Marcus Tullius Cicero (106–43 BC) was the greatest Roman orator, a leading statesman of the late Republic, and the primary transmitter of Greek philosophy to the Latin-speaking world. His speeches, philosophical treatises, and letters remain central texts in the study of Latin, rhetoric, and political philosophy. His concept of natural law — rooted in Stoic philosophy — became foundational for Christian political theology and Western jurisprudence.
:::

